# LOO-CV model selection and stacking {#loo}

## Leave-one-out cross-validation {#loo-cv}

After fitting, `fit_calibration_bayes()` computes **Pareto-smoothed
importance-sampling LOO-CV** (PSIS-LOO) for every converged model via
the `loo` package [@vehtari2017].
LOO-CV estimates the expected log predictive density (ELPD) for a
held-out observation without refitting:

$$
\widehat{\text{elpd}}_\text{loo} \;=\;
\sum_{i=1}^{N} \log p(y_i \mid y_{-i})
$$

The **Pareto-$k$** diagnostic flags observations whose importance
weights are unreliable:

| $k$ | Label | Action |
|-----|-------|--------|
| $< 0.5$ | Good | Reliable. |
| $0.5$–$0.7$ | OK | Slightly influential; results usable. |
| $0.7$–$1$ | Bad | Consider moment-matching correction. |
| $\ge 1$ | Very bad | LOO unreliable for this model. |

```{r loo-compare}
loo_comparison
```

```{r pareto-k,
    fig.cap="Pareto-k diagnostic for logistic4. Points above k = 0.7 (dashed line) flag high-leverage calibrators that disproportionately influence the fit."}
plot(loo_list[["logistic4"]],
     diagnostic   = "k",
