# Eligibility gating {#eligibility}

Before any model's posterior predictions are used for back-calculation,
curveRbayes subjects each fitted `curve_id` x model combination to
**eligibility gates**.
A model that fails a gate is excluded from the ensemble even if its
MCMC diagnostics are clean; its `$grid` and back-calculated
concentrations are not returned.

## The `rel_se` gate {#rel-se}

For each per-`curve_id` parameter $\theta_k$:

$$
\text{rel\_se}(\theta_k)
= \frac{\operatorname{posterior SD}(\theta_k)}{|\operatorname{posterior mean}(\theta_k)|}
$$

If any parameter's relative SE exceeds `max_rel_se` (default 5.0),
the `curve_id` x model combination is flagged ineligible.
This catches near-unidentified parameters where the likelihood is
essentially flat in one direction — formally valid MCMC but
meaningless predictions.

## The `dynamic_range` gate {#dynamic-range}

$$
\text{dynamic\_range}
= \frac{\hat{D}_k - \hat{A}_k}{\hat{A}_k + \epsilon}
$$

where $\hat{D}_k$ and $\hat{A}_k$ are posterior medians of the upper
and lower asymptotes for `curve_id` $k$.
A curve whose upper asymptote is less than the threshold multiple of
its lower asymptote lacks the breadth needed for reliable
back-calculation across the full concentration range.

```{r eligibility}
eligibility |>
  dplyr::select(model, curve_id, gate, passed, detail, eligible) |>
  dplyr::arrange(model, curve_id, gate) |>
  knitr::kable(digits = 3,
               caption = "Eligibility gate results. eligible = FALSE excludes that model x curve_id from back-calculation.")
```

```{r eligibility-summary}
eligibility |>
  dplyr::group_by(model) |>
  dplyr::summarise(
    n_curve_ids = dplyr::n_distinct(curve_id),
    n_failures  = sum(!eligible),
    all_passed  = all(eligible),
    .groups     = "drop"
  ) |>
  knitr::kable(caption = "Eligibility summary across all models.")
```

