# Back-calculating test samples {#backcalc}

## Why noise is NOT injected for test samples {#no-noise}

This is the most important conceptual distinction in the package.

When you run `predict_samples_bayes()` on observed test-sample
responses, the situation is fundamentally different from building
a CDAN grid:

> **The observed response $y_\text{obs}$ already IS the noisy
> measurement. Injecting noise again would be double-counting.**

The back-calculation task is: *given that the instrument returned
$y_\text{obs}$, what is the posterior distribution of the unknown
concentration $x$?*
This is a pure inversion problem:

$$
\hat{x}^{(s,k)}
= f^{-1}\!\left(y_\text{obs};\; \boldsymbol{\theta}_k^{(s)}\right)
$$

No noise draw appears.
The uncertainty in $\hat{x}^{(s,k)}$ arises solely from posterior
uncertainty in the curve parameters $\boldsymbol{\theta}_k^{(s)}$.

| Scenario | Function | Noise injected? | Source of uncertainty |
|---|---|---|---|
| CDAN precision grid | `predict_grid_bayes()` | ✅ Yes — Student-t($\nu$=4) | Parameter uncertainty **+** hypothetical measurement noise |
| Test sample back-calculation | `predict_samples_bayes()` | ❌ No | Parameter uncertainty only (noise already realised in $y_\text{obs}$) |

## Running back-calculation {#backcalc-run}

Test samples need only `curve_id` and the response column (`mfi`).
No `concentration` column is needed or expected — that is what we are
estimating.

```{r backcalc}
# Test samples: observed MFI values for curve_ids 1–3
test_samples <- data.frame(
  curve_id = c(1L, 1L, 2L, 2L, 3L, 3L),
  sampleid = paste0("S", 1:6),
  mfi      = c(12500, 8300, 14100, 9800, 11600, 7200)
)

# Stacked ensemble back-calculation
results <- predict_samples_bayes(
  fit       = fit,
  newdata   = test_samples,
  use_stack = TRUE,
  ci_level  = 0.95
)

results |>
  dplyr::select(curve_id, sampleid, mfi,
                conc_median, conc_lo95, conc_hi95) |>
  knitr::kable(digits = 3,
               caption = "Back-calculated concentrations. conc_* columns are on the log10(AU/mL) scale. conc_median is the posterior median; conc_lo95/conc_hi95 are the 95% credible interval bounds.")
```

```{r backcalc-plot,
    fig.cap="Posterior concentration estimates for six test samples (log10 scale). Points are posterior medians; error bars are 95% credible intervals. Samples whose MFI falls near the inflection point of the calibration curve have narrower CIs, consistent with the CDAN precision profiles in Section 9."}
results |>
  ggplot(aes(x = sampleid,
             y      = conc_median,
             ymin   = conc_lo95,
             ymax   = conc_hi95,
             colour = factor(curve_id))) +
  geom_pointrange(linewidth = 0.8, size = 0.7) +
  labs(
    x        = "Sample ID",
    y        = "log\u2081\u2080(concentration)  [AU/mL]",
    colour   = "curve_id",
    title    = "Back-calculated concentrations",
    subtitle = "Stacked ensemble · 95% credible intervals"
  ) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 12) +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")
```

